===Etymology===
Often said to come from {{der|en|nah|xoccolatl|xocolātl}} (e.g. American Heritage Dictionary 2000) or {{m|nah|chocolatl}} (e.g. [http://dictionary.com dictionary.com] 2006), which would be derived from {{m|nah|xococ||bitter}} and {{m|nah|atl|ātl|water}}, with an irregular change of ''x'' to ''ch''. However, the form {{m|nah||xocolātl}} is not directly attested, and {{m|nah|chocolatl}} does not appear in Nahuatl until the mid-18th century. Dakin and Wichmann (2000) propose that the ''chocol-'' element refers to a special wooden stick used to prepare chocolate, and suggest that the etymon is {{m|nah|chicolātl}}, a word found in several modern Nahuatl dialects. Yet another theory is that the prefix came from {{der|en|yua|chocol||hot}}.

In any case, the word ''chocolate'' reached English via {{etyl|es|en}} and the second element is probably the Nahuatl word {{m|nah|atl|ātl|water}}.

